      "topic": "data_engineering",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "target_sec": 80,
      "ref": "Slowly-changing dimensions",
      "figures": [],
      "question": "A dimension table must keep history of customer address changes so a historical sales report always shows the address valid at the time of each sale. The appropriate SCD pattern is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "letter": "A",
          "text": "Apply SCD Type 1 — overwrite the address on every single change to the record"
        },
        {
          "letter": "B",
          "text": "Delete the customer row each time the customer's address changes in the source system"
        },
        {
          "letter": "C",
          "text": "Apply SCD Type 0 — never allow the address column to be populated on a row"
        },
        {
          "letter": "D",
          "text": "SCD Type 2 — keep historical rows with valid-from / valid-to and an 'is_current' flag"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "D",
      "explanation": "Correct: D — Correct. SCD Type 2 (Kimball) preserves history by adding a new dimension row each time a tracked attribute changes, with valid-from / valid-to timestamps and typically an is_current boolean. Facts reference the dimension row that was current at event time (time-travel join), so historical reports always resolve to the historically-correct attribute value. It is the canonical pattern for dimensions where history matters (customer address, employee grade, product price list). Trade-off: more rows and slightly more complex joins.\n· A: Overwriting loses history — the opposite requirement.\n· B: Deleting the row loses the customer entirely. The task is to preserve history, not destroy records in the source system.\n· C: Never populating the address means you have no address at all, let alone history.",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Overwriting loses history — the opposite requirement.",
        "B": "Deleting the row loses the customer entirely. The task is to preserve history, not destroy records in the source system.",
        "C": "Never populating the address means you have no address at all, let alone history.",
        "D": "Correct. SCD Type 2 (Kimball) preserves history by adding a new dimension row each time a tracked attribute changes, with valid-from / valid-to timestamps and typically an is_current boolean. Facts reference the dimension row that was current at event time (time-travel join), so historical reports always resolve to the historically-correct attribute value. It is the canonical pattern for dimensions where history matters (customer address, employee grade, product price list). Trade-off: more rows and slightly more complex joins."
      }
