      "ref": "RPO vs RTO",
      "figures": [],
      "question": "A disaster-recovery plan states: 'in a regional outage, we can lose at most 15 minutes of data, and services must be back up within 2 hours'. The two quantities map to:",
      "options": [
        {
          "letter": "A",
          "text": "RPO equals 2 hours and RTO equals 15 minutes across all covered systems of the org"
        },
        {
          "letter": "B",
          "text": "They are synonymous terms that refer to exactly the same covered metric"
        },
        {
          "letter": "C",
          "text": "RPO equals 0 minutes; RTO equals the sum of 15 minutes plus 2 hours"
        },
        {
          "letter": "D",
          "text": "RPO = 15 minutes (acceptable data loss) and RTO = 2 hours (acceptable downtime)"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "D",
      "explanation": "Correct: D — Correct. RPO (Recovery Point Objective) is the maximum acceptable amount of DATA loss measured in time — 'how far back can we afford our last good copy to be?'. RTO (Recovery Time Objective) is the maximum acceptable DOWNTIME — 'how long can we afford the service to be unavailable?'. RPO drives backup frequency / replication lag; RTO drives failover automation, standby capacity and run-books. Both feed the Business Continuity Plan and influence cost-of-resilience decisions.\n· A: RPO / RTO are swapped across the covered systems of the org. RPO is about data-loss tolerance; RTO is about downtime tolerance.\n· B: They are two distinct metrics of a recovery plan.\n· C: RPO = 0 means no data loss, which contradicts the stated 15-minute acceptable-loss tolerance. And RTO isn't 'a sum'.",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "RPO / RTO are swapped across the covered systems of the org. RPO is about data-loss tolerance; RTO is about downtime tolerance.",
        "B": "They are two distinct metrics of a recovery plan.",
        "C": "RPO = 0 means no data loss, which contradicts the stated 15-minute acceptable-loss tolerance. And RTO isn't 'a sum'.",
        "D": "Correct. RPO (Recovery Point Objective) is the maximum acceptable amount of DATA loss measured in time — 'how far back can we afford our last good copy to be?'. RTO (Recovery Time Objective) is the maximum acceptable DOWNTIME — 'how long can we afford the service to be unavailable?'. RPO drives backup frequency / replication lag; RTO drives failover automation, standby capacity and run-books. Both feed the Business Continuity Plan and influence cost-of-resilience decisions."
      }
