      "ref": "Hot / warm / cold storage tiers",
      "figures": [],
      "question": "A data team designs a retention strategy for 10 years of transaction data. Recent 3 months are queried daily by BI; months 4–24 are queried a few times a month; years 3–10 are kept only for legal audit. The best-fit tiering is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "letter": "A",
          "text": "All 10 years of the transaction data kept continuously in the warehouse's expensive hot columnar tier with sub-second query latency end-to-end across all interactive analysts and BI users who access it"
        },
        {
          "letter": "B",
          "text": "Recent 3 months on hot columnar storage for BI; months 4–24 on warm object storage (standard) queryable via external tables; years 3–10 on cold / archival storage (Glacier / Archive) with policy-driven retrieval"
        },
        {
          "letter": "C",
          "text": "All the transaction data deleted after 30 days regardless of any legal, regulatory, contractual or audit retention obligation that might otherwise apply to the records held by the institution under Union or national law"
        },
        {
          "letter": "D",
          "text": "All 10 years of the transaction data kept exclusively on long-term magnetic-tape archival media, retrieved individually for every single BI query including interactive dashboards driving business decisions at short notice"
        }
      ],
      "correct": "B",
      "explanation": "Correct: B — Correct. A lifecycle-based tiering matches access pattern to cost: (1) HOT — low-latency columnar storage (Snowflake / BigQuery / Redshift / lakehouse silver/gold) for the 3 months used daily; (2) WARM — object storage (S3 / Azure Blob / GCS Standard) queryable via external tables / federation for months 4–24, trading a little latency for much lower cost; (3) COLD / ARCHIVE — S3 Glacier / Archive Tier / Azure Archive for years 3–10, with restore SLAs measured in hours and rock-bottom storage cost. Cloud lifecycle policies can transition objects automatically as they age. This preserves legal retention while controlling spend.\n· A: Keeping 10 years on hot storage with sub-second access is wasteful — old data doesn't need that tier.\n· C: Blanket 30-day deletion ignores legal retention obligations. Retention must be justified and tiered.\n· D: Tape can't serve interactive dashboards. Archive tiers are for cold access, not BI latency.",
      "explanations": {
        "A": "Keeping 10 years on hot storage with sub-second access is wasteful — old data doesn't need that tier.",
        "B": "Correct. A lifecycle-based tiering matches access pattern to cost: (1) HOT — low-latency columnar storage (Snowflake / BigQuery / Redshift / lakehouse silver/gold) for the 3 months used daily; (2) WARM — object storage (S3 / Azure Blob / GCS Standard) queryable via external tables / federation for months 4–24, trading a little latency for much lower cost; (3) COLD / ARCHIVE — S3 Glacier / Archive Tier / Azure Archive for years 3–10, with restore SLAs measured in hours and rock-bottom storage cost. Cloud lifecycle policies can transition objects automatically as they age. This preserves legal retention while controlling spend.",
        "C": "Blanket 30-day deletion ignores legal retention obligations. Retention must be justified and tiered.",
        "D": "Tape can't serve interactive dashboards. Archive tiers are for cold access, not BI latency."
      }
