      "explanation": "Correct: D — Correct. The modern pipeline encodes text with a pre-trained language model (BERT, RoBERTa, XLM-R, multilingual transformers) into a dense embedding, then either uses the model itself as a classifier (fine-tuning) or passes the embedding to a downstream classifier. This captures context, syntax and subtle semantic cues better than lexicon counts. Trade-offs: less interpretability, compute cost, and the need for careful handling of bias in the pre-training data.\n· A: Pure lexicon-based systems have been superseded by language-model embeddings — although lexicons still exist as a baseline. They remain brittle when vocabulary diverges.\n· B: Sentiment scores are one signal; they complement, not replace, qualitative research.\n· C: Modern multilingual models (XLM-R, mBERT, modern LLMs) handle many languages — including EU-24.",
